&lt;sounds of applause&gt;<br>
<br>
I don't have any corrections, really... just 4 vague comments.<br>
<br>
1)<br>
For &quot;the stars come out&quot;, you could alternately say &quot;hoshi ga kore kara mieru&quot; (starting now, the stars are visible) or (preferably) &quot;hoshi ga demasu&quot; (middle-level polite)/ &quot;hoshi ga deru&quot; (very relaxed, not polite but not necesarily rude, like wearing a T-shirt and ripped jeans).  Those last 2 translation-versions would follow the same pattern as hi-no-de (sunrise), where the &quot;de&quot; is the same kanji as the &quot;de&quot; in &quot;de-guchi&quot; (exit).<br>
<br>
2) <br>
Jill translates &quot;Elf&quot; as &quot;E-ru-fu&quot;, copying the sound but not the meaning.  This is a fairly good idea, since Japan doesn't have a tradition of elf-like (chaotic good slender mythical characters).  You run the risk of the Japanese audience not understanding, though... and &quot;erufu&quot; is a brand name for a car or a camera in Japan, I think.<br>
<br>
You could use a Japanese traditional mythical figure, but then you'll be trapped in the morphology &amp; modus-operandi of THAT group.  For example, Japanese &quot;KAPPA&quot; are fairly elf-like, but they're strictly found near water, have bowls on bald spots atop their heads which must ALWAYS be filled with water, have webbed feet, and are frequently drawn as being somewhat frog-like in coloring.<br>
<br>
The nearest OTHER Japanese mythological critter would be more TROLL-like... being kinda mean, living underground/in hell, and being as ugly as roadkill.<br>
<br>
There MAY be a standardized way of translating &quot;ELF&quot;, but I'm not an OTAKU (die-hard manga-zine fan), so I can't really help you there.<br>
<br>
The author uses the word &quot;demon&quot;, too, but there's a WEALTH of demon-like characters in Japanese mythology, so there's no problem translating there....unless you want to see a list of the different kinds of demons in Japan, so you can choose the closest match to your universe's &quot;demons&quot;.<br>
In general, &quot;oni&quot; would be a safe translation.<br>
<br>
3)<br>
A question of style:<br>
Let's take a quick peek at the song's content.  <br>
<br>
This is sung while someone's &quot;waking up their soul&quot;, but presumably it's sung at nightfall.<br>
The song starts as a nice sort of nature-y song from John Denver, but then kinda becomes a historical narrative like a Spanish &quot;ranchero&quot;, then drifts over into being a sort of call-to-arms like the Battle Hymn of the Republic.<br>
<br>
If you're SURE you want the content to move through these 3 widely different styles, OK... but if it were ME drawing the art, I'd be sure to show (in the artwork) that the singer is going through some style-and-tempo changes.<br>
<br>
4)<br>
Toward the end of the song, you say <br>
&quot;with intellect(sp?)<br>
brute force<br>
friendship and love<br>
we will<br>
prevail(sp?)&quot;<br>
That spelling's OK... but earlier on, you say &quot;nocturnal&quot; (an adjective) when you want &quot;night&quot; (a noun).<br>
Also, it seems kinda strange that you say &quot;intellect and brute force and friendship and love&quot;, because &quot;brute&quot; implies a lack of brains, and a bit of violence-for-the-sake-of-violence.  Perhaps you could replace &quot;brute force&quot; with &quot;pure strength&quot; or just &quot;strength&quot;  (= &quot;chikara&quot;, in Japanese) ?<br>
<br>
In the translation, I'm not really finding the line where tJillzip says &quot;to defeat the demons&quot;, which I'd translate (poorly) as &quot;oni-tachi wo taosu&quot;.  (oni = devil, tachi = plural, taosu = topple, vanquish, make-revolution-against)<br>
